## **Overview**

### **Purpose**

Sports clubs are shifting more and more toward a monthly membership model as entrepreneurs in the space benefit from having predictable monthly revenue. However, with more customers paying membership, this makes it incredibly difficult and awkward to turn people away if a session reaches capacity. The solution to this is to use a bookings system for Members and business owners to make and manage bookings according to the club's timetable. Unfortunately, many of the software solutions for this are extremely expensive and contain a litany of features that small/medium business owners will never use\!

The OpenClubManager is an open-source, lightweight bookings and customer management system designed to solve the above issues. OpenClubManager is highly customisable and gives entrepreneurs or devs the opportunity to create their own system using our app as a starting point. OpenClubManager allows business owners to provide their customers with a hassle-free, well-designed booking system that allows them to book sessions, Manage their membership, manage their data and more, with the option to house more than one participant per user account (e.g a parent who wants to book classes for multiple children) This empowers business owners to track attendance, manage membership options and prices, take payment, create and edit the weekly timetable of classes, cancel sessions, track session capacity and more\!

### **Target Audience**

This software is intended for use by small to medium business owners and entrepreneurs in the Sport, fitness and leisure industry. Businesses that need to begin scaling up (e.g moving to a more full-time timetable of sessions) but do not yet have the budget for the current Club management systems available.

## **User Stories**

### **Must-Have User Stories**

1. **User: List view of bookable sessions (Minimum viable product)**  
   As a User I can filter the list of upcoming classes by participant age group, class type or day of session so that I can more easily navigate the timetable and book the correct session  
   Acceptance criteria:  
* List view of Bookable classes, filter options as stated  
* Clickable events from list to open booking form  
* Option to go back  
* form validates against participant age to catch errors  
2. **User account management (Allauth)**  
    As a user I can register for an account so that I can access features which require user auth  
   Acceptance criteria:  
* User can register an account  
* User can Log in, logout  
    
3. **Admin: Write, view, edit and delete bookings**  
   As a site admin I can view, add, edit and delete bookings so that I can manage customer requests and session attendance  
   Acceptance criteria:  
* Super user can view all bookings  
* Super user can edit, add and delete all bookings  
* Super user can search and filter bookings by class type, date, etc.  
    
4. **User: Create, View, Update and delete bookings**  
   As a User I can create, view, edit and delete bookings on my account so that \*\*I can manage my own bookings and view upcoming events \*\*  
   Acceptance criteria:  
* User can select a class instance  
* User fills out form pre-populated with some information including class instance ID  
* User can view list of upcoming bookings  
* User can view a list or previous bookings  
* user can edit or delete bookings, generating a new confirmation and logging a new datetime of booking updated.  
    
    
5. **Admin:  Create and maintain timetable of available sessions**  
   As a site admin I can create, edit and delete timetables so that I can easily manage changes to class timetables and update what the customer sees  
   Acceptance criteria:  
* site admin able to edit a timetable to be displayed to users using existing class/session types from the database  
* Site admin able to create, edit and delete class types  
* New timetables stored as objects which can be displayed  
* Site admin able to choose which timetable is displayed

**Should-Have User Stories**

1. **User: Interactive Timetable UI**  
   As a User I can Open a booking form via an interactive, clickable timetable view so that I can visualise and select the correct class instance more easily  
   Acceptance criteria:  
* Timetable view displays stored timetable model  
* User can click on a class instance displayed in this view which will open a booking form prepopulated with the class instance id  
* User can submit this form successfully

2. **User: Multiple participants**  
   As a user (parent) I can add details of my children who attend the club so that I can manage multiple particpants bookings from one account  
   Acceptance criteria:  
* When User registers account, they are given form for "Participant", they can add additional participants or click "This is me/ this is my child" at end of form  
* Multiple "Participants" can be added to one booking  
* Parent user can filter bookings list by participant

3. **User: Pay for sessions online**   
   As a user I can pay for a session or membership before a booking is confirmed so that I can attend the session cashless  
   Acceptance criteria:  
* User can pay securely via stripe  
* superuser can set up and integrate their stripe account to receive funds  
* A record of the payment can be confirmed via a receipt

4. **Admin: Session attendance register**   
   As a site admin I can print an attendance register for a class instance or take an electronic register so that I can track attendance  
   Acceptance criteria:  
* Admin can view attendance register  
* admin can choose to print a simply formatted attendance register for a class instance  
* Attendance can be tracked on class instance as a sub-class

5. **User: Create recurring bookings**  
   As a Membership user I can set bookings to recur every week or every month so that I can spend less time creating bookings each week  
   Acceptance criteria:  
* Feature displays if user is a verified member  
* Feature adds duplicate bookings to subsequent weeks  
* User is notified if any subsequent weeks are not bookable (e.g holidays or over-capacity sessions)  
* Non-member users can click this option and redirect to membership options  
* super user can make and manage membership options  
* superuser can override member restrictions to create recurring bookings on customer behalf

### **Could-Have User Stories**

1. **Admin: Email integration for notifications, receipts and communication with customers**  
   As a superuser I can set up mass email integration so that I can communicate with customers, send and receive booking confirmations and payment receipts via an automated system, saving time and money.  
   Acceptance criteria:  
* Registration required email address, permission for confirmations required  
* Customer can click a button to view, print or receive booking summaries or receipts for any booking on their account  
* Superuser can choose to be notified via email of any new bookings  
* super user can choose to send the customer or the admin email a copy of any booking  
* super user can set admin recipient email address for this feature

2. **Admin: Add holidays, cancel sessions, adjust capacity of sessions**  
   As a superuser I can Add exceptions to the calendar that make sessions non-bookable so that \**I can manage opening and closing times, holidays, cancellations and product discontinuation*  
   Acceptance criteria:  
* Easily set new holiday periods via form  
* Set Existing class types as "Non-bookable" without deleting them.  
* I can select a class instance and select "Remove all subsequent sessions of this type"  
* Cancel sessions via form which send notification to customers via email, sms or app notification

3. **User/admin: Calendar view of all timetabled sessions**  
   As a User/site admin I can view a calendar of upcoming sessions so that I can better visualise and plan my attendance  
   Acceptance criteria:  
* Calendar view displays user all bookings  
* Calendar view superuser displays ALL timetabled sessions  
* Super user can CRUD via calendar view

4. **User: Google calendar integration**  
   As a user I can send bookings to my google calendar so that I can be reminded of upcoming bookings via my mobile device  
   Acceptance criteria:  
* Google API for event insert returns successful  
* Front end user can click to integrate their google calendar via Oauth  
* USer can click "Add to google calendar" button on booking summary to add event via API

5. **Admin: Authorised devices, geofencing and automatic login.**  
   As a site admin I can click "Remember me on this device for 7 days so that I can access the app quickly and easily during the work week  
   Acceptance criteria:  
* checkbox to remember device for 7 days  
* auth temporarily stores identifying info for current device  
* auth sets timeout to 7 days

## **Design Decisions**

**Wireframes:**![][image1]This wireframe gives a pared-down view of the timetabled sessions with a list view which is highly achievable. I made this the MVP because I think it is adequate user experience while also being achievable with django’s built-in capability. Other wireframes I produced would require me to learn how to generate calendars or learn to use 3rd party modules. While I remain open to this, I was concerned about the time constraint. 

**Calendar wireframes**

![][image2]

Initially, I thought of the calendar view as the goal for the booking system but given the unique context of the Open Club Manager use-case. I think a weekly view would actually be sufficient. I believe the only time the monthly view would be used is when a customer wants to know if the club is running during school holidays or over the festive period etc. This is something the business owner likely already includes in their website. The only other use for the monthly view would be to book special events (e.g Summer camp, winter workshops, one-off events etc) well in advance.

Notable decisions in this view: On desktop, the left-side navigation panel. This is an aesthetic choice as is may allow the site to use the rule of thirds. Also notable is the right-side navigation panel on a landscape mobile device. This is intended to improve UX as most people are right handed, however I realised recently that having the nav so close to where a hand may be intermittently resting increases the likelihood that the user will accidentally navigate away from the current page.

**User bookings view:**

![][image3]

This view allows the user to view a list of bookings. The bookings are separated into “Upcoming” and “previous” tabs to avoid past bookings from interfering if a user is trying to find an upcoming booking while also maintaining a record of the past bookings.

In this wireframe, I initially thought the portrait mobile view should still have a side panel but that it should be collapsable. Instead I opted for a collapsable nav that fills the screen from the top-down. I think this provides a clean and clear experience.

**Single booking view**

![][image4]

I initially thought I’d have the bookings use a separate template and url so the “back” button was essential. Instead of this I opted to use an accordion menu where clicking on a booking in the list shows the booking confirmation in the accordion content. This gives a more intuitive experience.

**Entity relationship Diagram**

![][image5]

I intended for the user to list multiple Participants under their account as many entry-level sports clubs are attended by children of varying age groups so I wanted the parents to need only one account to manage and pay for their child’s attendance. Nearly all of these models received modifications during the development process to improve functionality or implement new features. 

I also added a “Customizations” model, which is not linked to any of the other models but is used extensively in the html template files to allow admins to set colours, logo, contact details, native currency and more this feature became one that I am proud of and I believe would be used extensively by the target audience. Using a model for customization also gave me the idea to use a model for Stripe implementation so that the business owner can input their stripe API keys in the admin panel for plug+play functionality.

**Colour Palette**

![][image6]

While The site’s colours are fully customizable in the admin panel, for the OpenClubManager defaults I opted for a set of blues to provide a calming experience that felt open and clear. The additional colours, (red, yellow, teal) are the colours of the example class-types I created but these too are controlled by a ColorField in the model so the admin will select a color when creating a new record.

### **Accessibility Considerations**

I checked this palette against different types of colour blindness and did not find any issues with contrast. I have used a dark font colour on any greys, light blues, whites and light text on dark backgrounds. These font colours are also customizable as “brand-text-white” and “brand-text-dark”. Semantic html used throughout.

**Font:**

![][image7]

I wanted a clear and readable sans-serif font with less convolution ( e.g the loop-sided style of “g” or the top-tailed “a”)

## **AI Tools Usage**

No AI was used in the design process. All design decisions were made by me independent of any AI tools. Ai was used during development to help me quickly implement features but not in any creative capacity. This site also contains zero AI generated imagery.

## **Features Implementation**

### **Core Features (Must-Haves)**

* **User Authentication:** Users can register, log in and logout of their account. They can also change their username, email address and other user details inside the account details page  
* **Timetable list view:** Users can view a list of timetabled sessions and click on them to open a booking form for that session. Classes are sorted by date with the template only showing upcoming sessions to Users (rather than showing all sessions in this calendar week, today’s date is used as a cut-off)   
* **Multiple Participants:** Users can create, read, update and delete participant records associated with their user account. Users can have multiple participants under one user account.  
* **User- Booking CRUD:** Users can Create, read, update and delete bookings for the timetabled sessions.   
* **Admin- User records CRUD:** Site admins can Create, read, update and delete all user-generated records, including: user details, bookings, participants  
* **Admin- Timetable CRUD:** Site admins can create, read, update and delete timetables which, when set to “Active” will be shown to the users on the dashboard.  
* 

### **Advanced Features (Should-Haves)**

* **Interactive Timetable UI:** \[FEATURE UNDER DEVELOPMENT\] I ran out of time to make this work the way I wanted. The table successfully reflects what the admin inputs as the parameters for the timetable instance. The idea was that the admin could click an empty cell and add a session to the timetable from a form that appears inside a modal, pre-populated with the time and day of the clicked cell. This was all working on a fresh page but became buggy after submitting one session. Functionality returned after refreshing the page but I removed the feature for now partly due to the difference in quality of this feature compared with the rest of the site. But mainly it was removed as I felt it would take up too much time to get it working perfectly. However, this will be my first priority after the submission deadline. To view it in the current state, use  /timetable/0001 in the URL  
* **Booking Confirmations:** I added this feature during development as a quick and effective short-term alternative to emailing confirmations to the user. The user can download their booking confirmation as a PDF. The template for the PDF and booking confirmation are extremely similar to provide stylistic consistency. This of course achieves the same goal as the emailed confirmations which is to give the User a datetime-stamped copy of their booking.  
* **Admin Customizations:** Given that the target audience for this app is small-medium businesses and it is primarily an interface between that business and it’s customers, I decided to add customizations so that the Site admin can adjust the site’s defaults to match their brand. All customizations are available in the admin panel  
* **Contact form:** For similar reasons as above, I added this feature to facilitate customer interactions in the case of a bug or error. As the admin has full CRUD functionality for all records, they can likely perform any task a customer is struggling with. This is the last line of defense for a positive UX

### **Optional Features (Could-Haves)**

* **Stripe Integration:**  Users can now Pay for their sessions via the Stripe checkout API if stripe has been set up by the admin. If it has not, the page will not give a “pay now” option. This feature allows customers to attend without cash and allows the business to flow more freely (e.g avoiding a line of customers waiting to pay before the session starts, allowing late-arriving customers to join in without needing a staff member to come and take payment midway through a session) This also allows the Business owner to more easily track their income from sessions as stripe’s dashboard will show them analytics.

**Next Features to implement:**

Interactive Timetable UI, Recurring bookings, Session attendance tracking, Google calendar integration, Admin-scheduled timetable closures\&cancellations.

## **AI Tools Usage**

Perplexity AI:

While I typically use AI only to quickly interpret errors and handle the grunt work of repetitive, simple code. There were a few features of OpenClub Manager in which I used AI extensively. In Particular, I used Perplexity to quickly integrate Stripe as the documentation for stripe did not offer a django setup guide.Perplexity generated the bulk of the code for this feature While I dealt with problem solving and logic flow to fix the AI’s suggested code. 

I also used perplexity to make my code more concise in some sections and more readable in others.

Another way I used Perplexity was to test the waters when considering adding a feature on a whim as I didn’t want to engage in any complicated implementation for small non-essential features. I was pleasantly surprised in some cases by the efficacy of the Ai’s code but at other times, this cost me hours of debugging.

The functional code and implementation of WeasyPrint to create PDFs from the Booking confirmation screens for example, was almost entirely Perplexity. I applied the styling and content of the pdf template and checked over the code for any problems but the core view.py code and structure was taken directly from Perplexity.

 I also used Perplexity to help me ideate on the Account details view, in which I wanted “edit” buttons which would allow a user to edit the model instance one field at a time, without being redirected to a separate template. Perplexity supplied some code which I modified heavily to make work but the general structure and order of operations remains mostly the same.

While implementing the navbar for mobile, I used Perplexity to create a smoother animation when expanding or collapsing the menu.

## **AI Tools Usage**

Perplexity AI:

Perplexity was extremely useful in helping me quickly interpret error messages and offer solutions or tweaks to my code. At times, when I was at a loss with a bug and I couldn’t find it, I would copy+paste my code into perplexity and ask it to explain to me what that code does. This allowed me to separate what I thought the code does from what it actually does and I was able to fix a couple of bugs this way. (The edit+save buttons on the account details screen broke after I added a modal for the “createParticipant” form and )

That said, The periodic use of AI to check my code for errors led to very few validation errors at this stage.

When testing my code for Pep8 compliance, I quickly discovered it was far more efficient to prompt Perplexity to reformat my code to PEP-8 guidelines and then run the result through diffchecker to make sure all functionality is preserved. This solved the vast majority of the issues, though it seems the AI has a blind spot for line-length.

## **Deployment**

### **Deployment Process**

I deployed the project via Heroku, I did this early in the development process and would push to git hub and check heroku was building correctly at least once a day. 

There was one day where I encountered some errors as I had incorrectly set up django-encrypted-model-fields==0.6.5

I was encountering other issues with this module so I opted to remove it temporarily due to time constraints. I intend to add this module again after the submission deadline for this project as I would like to encrypt certain API secret keys for 3rd party integrations (e.g google calendar, stripe)

There were no other notable issues with deployment.

All code for this project was written in visual studio integrated development environment. Github was used for version control and the application was deployed to heroku from github.

**Deployment instructions**

### **Pre deployment**

* To ensure successful deployment with heroku, it's good practice to make sure that the requirements.txt file is kept up to date so as that imported python modules are configured correctly.  
* A Procfile is required to allow heroku deployment to be configured to a gunicorn web app.  
* In settings.py configure the ALLOWED\_HOSTS list the format \['app\_name.heroku.com', 'localhost'\], make sure all static files and directories are configured correctly.  
* All environment variables on the env.py which gitignored on the repo must be configured correctly with the database url, cloundinary url and secret key.

### **Deploying with heroku**

After account setup, the steps were as follows:

* Click the "create new app" button on heroku  
* Create a unique name for the app  
* Select region (Europe was selected for this project)  
* Click "create app"  
* Select the deployment method (github was used for this project)  
* Search for the github repository name (it was OpenClubManager for this project)  
* Click connect  
* There is an option to use manual deployment or automatic deployment. Make sure main branch is selected  
* In the settings tab select reveal config vars. Input the required hidden variables  
* Select nodejs and python as the buildpack  
* Deploy  
* After the first deployment you will see a message saying "your app was successfully deployed" and there will be a "view" button to take you to your deployed application

The live link for this project can be found here \- https://openclubmanager-fbf0e93c3ef0.herokuapp.com/

### **Fork this repository:**

* Go to the GitHub repository  
* Click on the Fork button in the upper right-hand corner

### **Clone this repository:**

* Go to the GitHub repository  
* Click the Code button near the top of the page  
* Select 'HTTPS', 'SSH', or 'Github CLI', depending on how you would like to clone  
* Click the copy button to copy the URL to your clipboard  
* Open Git Bash  
* Change the current working directory to where you want the cloned directory  
* Type git clone and paste the URL ($ git clone [https://github.com/YOUR-USERNAME/YOUR-REPOSITORY](https://github.com/YOUR-USERNAME/YOUR-REPOSITORY))  
* Press enter to create your clone locally

Note: The difference between clone and fork is, you need permissions to push back to the original from a clone, but not a fork because a fork will be completely your own new project.

## **Reflection on Development Process**

### **Successes**

This is the first time I’ve used AI to help me code and I think it allowed me to achieve some advanced features in relatively little time. I also found that having a Well-laid out ERD really helped as I was able to produce my initial models in less than an hour of typing.

### **Challenges**

There were significant challenges when giving AI more complex tasks but I found that feeding it the relevant code to allow it to understand the full context of a request helped a lot. That said, I don’t think I’ll rely on AI for complex multi-file code again. It really shines with more specific requests and error interpretation in my opinion

I also faced some challenges with identifying modules that were compatible with the version of Django I was using

### **Final Thoughts**

I struggled with Scope creep during this project and found myself giving time to non-essential features before I had finished my Must-have features. My use of the github project board helped with this but I think I should use a strategy to break down my time a bit more. Perhaps something like a pomodoro timer that would force me to decide what I want to commit each chunk of time to, effectively mitigating my distractibility

I am also feeling good about my ability to use Django at this stage and I found myself thinking in an object-oriented way throughout. At the start of the project I felt as though I had no idea how th files related to one another but now, toward the end of the project I feel I have a better grasp of the way information flows between files for any given task.  

## **Future Improvements**

I am going to continue to  improve Open Club manager and I’d like to action the following features: 

Interactive Timetable UI, Recurring bookings, Session attendance tracking, Google calendar integration, Admin-scheduled timetable closures & cancellations.

Beyond that, I think I’d like to add quality of life features to the admin panel

I believe these will elevate the project from the MVP to a well-appointed app. I will also need to spend some time creating a small guide for the site admin on deployment and the customization options.
